sion copies the entire content into a new byte slice, even for multi-line JSONL where the parse will fail almost immediately. For large transcripts (tens of MB), this is a wasted allocation on the hot path.\\n\\n  **Suggested fix:** Add a cheap heuristic to skip the full-parse attempt when the content is clearly multi-line JSONL. For example, check if the content contains a newline followed by a `{` or `[` character:\\n\\n  ```go\\n  // Skip full-parse attempt for multi-line JSONL (avoids copying large content).\\n  // A newline followed by '{' or '[' strongly indicates JSONL, not a single JSON value.\\n  // Pretty-printed JSON has newlines too, but they're followed by whitespace/closing tokens.\\n  if idx := strings.IndexByte(trimmedFull, '\\\\n'); idx >= 0 {\\n      afterNewline := strings.TrimLeft(trimmedFull[idx+1:], \\\" \\\\t\\\\r\\\")\\n      if len(afterNewline) > 0 && (afterNewline[0] == '{' || afterNewline[0] == '[') {\\n          goto lineByLine\\n      }\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  This avoids the allocation for the dominant case (JSONL) while still attempting full-parse for pretty-printed JSON (where lines start with whitespace, `\\\"`, `}`, `]`, etc.).\\n\\n  Alternatively, the simpler but less precise version: just check `bytes.Count(content, '\\\\n') > 0 && content starts with '{'` -- if the first line is a complete JSON object (which `json.Valid` could check on just the first line), it's JSONL. But the above heuristic is probably sufficient.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n- **[redact/redact.go:168-191]** For an even simpler approach: use `json.NewDecoder` instead of `json.Unmarshal`. A decoder reads from an `io.Reader` (wrap with `strings.NewReader`) and does not require a `[]byte` copy. Then check `dec.More()` after decoding one value -- if there is more data, it is JSONL, not a single JSON value. This avoids both the copy and the heuristic:\\n\\n  ```go\\n  dec := json.NewDecoder(strings.NewReader(trimmedFull))\\n  var parsed any\\n  if err := dec.Decode(&parsed); err == nil && !dec.More() {\\n      // Single JSON value -- use field-aware redaction\\n      repls := collectJSONLReplacements(parsed)\\n      // ...\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  This is zero-copy, semantically exact (no heuristic needed), and handles all edge cases (single object, single array, pretty-printed, etc.). The `dec.More()` check distinguishes \\\"single JSON value\\\" from \\\"first of many JSONL lines.\\\" This is the cleanest fix.\\n\\n- **[redact/redact.go:177-188]** Previous review's duplication note still applies. Extract the replacement loop into a helper.\\n\\n### Not a Problem\\n\\n- **Hot-path overhead of the new code block:** The `json.Unmarshal` (or decoder) adds microseconds for the common JSONL case (fails fast on second line). The real work in this function is `String()` / gitleaks detection per line, which dwarfs the parse attempt. The new block is not a meaningful performance regression.\\n\\n- **Single-line JSONL taking the new path instead of the old:** Both paths produce identical results. The new path is actually slightly more efficient for single-line input because it avoids `strings.Split` and the line-by-line loop overhead.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- The design correctly identifies that pretty-printed JSON is the problematic case and handles it with a clean fallback pattern.\\n- The failed-parse-then-fallback approach is idiomatic Go and easy to reason about.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- Overall assessment: **APPROVE** (with suggestions)\\n- The efficiency concerns raised in the review request are largely non-issues in practice. The one real waste is the `[]byte` copy for large JSONL files on the full-parse attempt. Using `json.NewDecoder` with `strings.NewReader` eliminates this entirely with no heuristics needed -- that would be the ideal fix. The duplication from review-01 is still outstanding.\\n- Estimated effort to address: 15-20 minutes (decoder refactor + extract helper).\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":999,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":39057,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":999,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":2,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ6uGTCPTDu2L8i5sTPq4\",\"uuid\":\"4a43d367-f7c4-47bd-8b93-3011942c4005\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a9c639c3cd2ffe777\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01VbUBpFT3ZNMvGjQVgazfhM\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Xbjs1yDW7z7o6A9VCoZijR\",\"uuid\":\"19247db0-53ab-4772-952f-2d6a23a5f8cd\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14:17:44.902Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"43cdaaf0-30f7-405b-b7e0-c8d98b817d6b\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-fix\",\"slug\":\"misty-splashing-elephant\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"19247db0-53ab-4772-952f-2d6a23a5f8cd\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01GZ8wnQCjKXjE4XK9N5Ah3b\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"File created successfully at: /Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments/docs/requirements/opencode-redact-fix/review-02.md\"}]},\"uuid\":\"363b0705-2daa-4d0f-b695-8c7d9dd7afae\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14:17:44.904Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a9c639c3cd2ffe777\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01VbUBpFT3ZNMvGjQVgazfhM\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Xbjs1yDW7z7o6A9VCoZijR\",\"uuid\":\"33a44f17-ef0b-4f6e-a6fb-1928a78e5d79\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14:17:44.904Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"43cdaaf0-30f7-405b-b7e0-c8d98b817d6b\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-fix\",\"slug\":\"misty-splashing-elephant\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"33a44f