    21→\\n    22→**Verdict: Negligible in practice, but worth understanding.** In Go, `strings.TrimSpace` does NOT always allocate. It returns a substring slice of the original string's backing memory when it only trims whitespace from the edges. The only allocation is the string header (16 bytes on 64-bit). For a 50MB transcript, the trimmed string shares the same backing array -- no 50MB copy occurs.\\n    23→\\n    24→The real allocation concern is on line 171: `[]byte(trimmedFull)` -- this DOES copy the full content into a new byte slice for `json.Unmarshal`. For multi-line JSONL (the common case), this means allocating a full copy of the content just to have `Unmarshal` fail on the first syntax error.\\n    25→\\n    26→### Concern 3: Cost of failed `json.Unmarshal` on multi-line JSONL\\n    27→\\n    28→**Verdict: Fast failure, acceptable overhead.** For typical JSONL content (multiple `{...}\\\\n{...}\\\\n` lines), `json.Unmarshal` on the full content will parse the first JSON object, then hit the second line's `{` and return a syntax error. The Go JSON decoder does not scan the entire input before failing -- it fails at the first unexpected token after a complete value. So for a 50MB JSONL file with 10,000 lines, the failed parse only reads the first line (~5KB), not all 50MB.\\n    29→\\n    30→However, the `[]byte(trimmedFull)` conversion on line 171 still copies all 50MB before the parser touches it. This is the actual waste.\\n    31→\\n    32→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    33→\\n    34→- **[redact/redact.go:171]** The `[]byte(trimmedFull)` conversion copies the entire content into a new byte slice, even for multi-line JSONL where the parse will fail almost immediately. For large transcripts (tens of MB), this is a wasted allocation on the hot path.\\n    35→\\n    36→  **Suggested fix:** Add a cheap heuristic to skip the full-parse attempt when the content is clearly multi-line JSONL. For example, check if the content contains a newline followed by a `{` or `[` character:\\n    37→\\n    38→  ```go\\n    39→  // Skip full-parse attempt for multi-line JSONL (avoids copying large content).\\n    40→  // A newline followed by '{' or '[' strongly indicates JSONL, not a single JSON value.\\n    41→  // Pretty-printed JSON has newlines too, but they're followed by whitespace/closing tokens.\\n    42→  if idx := strings.IndexByte(trimmedFull, '\\\\n'); idx >= 0 {\\n    43→      afterNewline := strings.TrimLeft(trimmedFull[idx+1:], \\\" \\\\t\\\\r\\\")\\n    44→      if len(afterNewline) > 0 && (afterNewline[0] == '{' || afterNewline[0] == '[') {\\n    45→          goto lineByLine\\n    46→      }\\n    47→  }\\n    48→  ```\\n    49→\\n    50→  This avoids the allocation for the dominant case (JSONL) while still attempting full-parse for pretty-printed JSON (where lines start with whitespace, `\\\"`, `}`, `]`, etc.).\\n    51→\\n    52→  Alternatively, the simpler but less precise version: just check `bytes.Count(content, '\\\\n') > 0 && content starts with '{'` -- if the first line is a complete JSON object (which `json.Valid` could check on just the first line), it's JSONL. But the above heuristic is probably sufficient.\\n    53→\\n    54→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    55→\\n    56→- **[redact/redact.go:168-191]** For an even simpler approach: use `json.NewDecoder` instead of `json.Unmarshal`. A decoder reads from an `io.Reader` (wrap with `strings.NewReader`) and does not require a `[]byte` copy. Then check `dec.More()` after decoding one value -- if there is more data, it is JSONL, not a single JSON value. This avoids both the copy and the heuristic:\\n    57→\\n    58→  ```go\\n    59→  dec := json.NewDecoder(strings.NewReader(trimmedFull))\\n    60→  var parsed any\\n    61→  if err := dec.Decode(&parsed); err == nil && !dec.More() {\\n    62→      // Single JSON value -- use field-aware redaction\\n    63→      repls := collectJSONLReplacements(parsed)\\n    64→      // ...\\n    65→  }\\n    66→  ```\\n    67→\\n    68→  This is zero-copy, semantically exact (no heuristic needed), and handles all edge cases (single object, single array, pretty-printed, etc.). The `dec.More()` check distinguishes \\\"single JSON value\\\" from \\\"first of many JSONL lines.\\\" This is the cleanest fix.\\n    69→\\n    70→- **[redact/redact.go:177-188]** Previous review's duplication note still applies. Extract the replacement loop into a helper.\\n    71→\\n    72→### Not a Problem\\n    73→\\n    74→- **Hot-path overhead of the new code block:** The `json.Unmarshal` (or decoder) adds microseconds for the common JSONL case (fails fast on second line). The real work in this function is `String()` / gitleaks detection per line, which dwarfs the parse attempt. The new block is not a meaningful performance regression.\\n    75→\\n    76→- **Single-line JSONL taking the new path instead of the old:** Both paths produce identical results. The new path is actually slightly more efficient for single-line input because it avoids `strings.Split` and the line-by-line loop overhead.\\n    77→\\n    78→### Praise\\n    79→\\n    80→- The design correctly identifies that pretty-printed JSON is the problematic case and handles it with a clean fallback pattern.\\n    81→- The failed-parse-then-fallback approach is idiomatic Go and easy to reason about.\\n    82→\\n    83→## Summary\\n    84→\\n    85→- Overall assessment: **APPROVE** (with suggestions)\\n    86→- The efficiency concerns raised in the review request are largely non-issues in practice. The one real waste is the `[]byte` copy for large JSONL files on the full-parse attempt. Using `json.NewDecoder` with `strings.NewReader` eliminates this entirely with no heuristics needed -- that would be the ideal fix. The duplication from review-01 is still outstanding.\\n    87→- Estimated effort to address: 15-20 minutes (decoder refactor + extract helper).\\n    88→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"67a90e52-c899-46e7-96be-9b168a91bf88\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14