ing(r[0])\\n          if err != nil {\\n              return \\\"\\\", err\\n          }\\n          replJSON, err := jsonEncodeString(r[1])\\n          if err != nil {\\n              return \\\"\\\", err\\n          }\\n          s = strings.ReplaceAll(s, origJSON, replJSON)\\n      }\\n      return s, nil\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  Both call sites collapse to `return applyJSONReplacements(content, repls)` (full-content path) and `result, err := applyJSONReplacements(line, repls)` (line-by-line path). This removes 12 duplicated lines and creates a single place to change if the replacement strategy evolves (e.g., adding a length guard, logging, or switching from `ReplaceAll` to indexed replacement).\\n\\n- **[redact/redact.go:171] Unnecessary `[]byte` copy for the full-parse attempt.** As review-02 noted, `json.Unmarshal([]byte(trimmedFull), ...)` copies the entire content into a byte slice. For multi-line JSONL (the common case), the parse fails quickly but the allocation is already made. The `json.NewDecoder` approach from review-02 is the cleanest fix:\\n\\n  ```go\\n  dec := json.NewDecoder(strings.NewReader(trimmedFull))\\n  var parsed any\\n  if err := dec.Decode(&parsed); err == nil && !dec.More() {\\n      // single JSON value -- field-aware redaction\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  This is zero-copy and also semantically tighter: `!dec.More()` confirms it is a single JSON value rather than relying on `Unmarshal` happening to succeed on multi-line input where the first line is valid JSON (which it would, producing incorrect behavior -- see edge case below).\\n\\n### Important Edge Case\\n\\n- **[redact/redact.go:169-191] Single valid JSON line followed by more JSONL lines.** Consider input like:\\n\\n  ```\\n  {\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"hello\\\"}\\n  {\\\"role\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"sk-secret-key-abc123xyz\\\"}\\n  ```\\n\\n  `strings.TrimSpace` produces the full two-line string. `json.Unmarshal` on this will parse the first line as a complete JSON object and succeed (Go's `json.Unmarshal` ignores trailing data after a valid top-level value). The function then returns early using only the first line's parsed structure, and the second line (containing a secret) is never examined.\\n\\n  **This is a correctness bug.** The `json.NewDecoder` + `dec.More()` fix addresses it, because `dec.More()` returns true when there is remaining data after the first decoded value, causing the code to fall through to line-by-line processing.\\n\\n  *Edit: Actually, `json.Unmarshal` in Go does NOT ignore trailing data -- it returns an error if there are extra bytes after the first value. So this edge case may not trigger. But it is worth verifying with a test, because the behavior is not obvious and could vary across Go versions. The decoder approach makes the intent explicit and removes the ambiguity.*\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n- **[redact/redact.go:168] `trimmedFull` naming.** The name is functional but reads oddly. Consider `stripped` or simply inline it: `content = strings.TrimSpace(content)` at the top of the function, since the original `content` value is not used after the trim (the line-by-line path re-splits from `content`, but trimming outer whitespace does not affect `strings.Split` on `\\\\n` in any meaningful way for JSONL). This eliminates the extra variable entirely.\\n\\n- **[redact/redact_test.go:475-513] Test only checks \\\"no REDACTED\\\" rather than structural preservation.** The pretty-printed JSON test asserts that no `REDACTED` marker appears and that specific IDs survive. It does not verify that the output is still valid JSON or that the whitespace/formatting is preserved byte-for-byte (the stated goal). Adding `if result != input` would strengthen the \\\"no false positive\\\" assertion. For the secrets test, checking valid JSON output would catch any corruption from partial replacement.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/types.go:85] The `ID` field addition is fine.** `omitempty` handles backward compatibility with older OpenCode versions. No concerns.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- The comments in the new code block are excellent -- they explain the \\\"why\\\" (pretty-printed JSON lines are not individually valid JSON, leading to entropy-based corruption) rather than just the \\\"what.\\\" Future readers will understand the motivation immediately.\\n- The test in `TestJSONLContent_PrettyPrintedJSON_IDsPreserved` is well-structured: it validates a precondition (entropy threshold) before asserting behavior, which makes test failures self-explanatory.\\n- Good separation of concerns: the two new tests cover orthogonal cases (IDs preserved vs. secrets still caught).\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- Overall assessment: **REQUEST CHANGES**\\n- Two issues remain from prior reviews (duplication, allocation), both straightforward to fix. The `json.NewDecoder` refactor also addresses a potential ambiguity around `Unmarshal` behavior with trailing data.\\n- Estimated effort: 15-20 minutes total for both fixes.\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":3566,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":30529,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":3566,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ6uSSE7whBMYh58VBoba\",\"uuid\":\"dac2f322-4f81-43ac-bbbf-4efecd5b20c6\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"af28736b6e89c4941\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01VbUBpFT3ZNMvGjQVgazfhM\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01AyGLbS84ELEt2rZyHx881S\",\"uuid\":\"267ba94e-9be5-432d-9fea-24321f861156\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14:19:54.543Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"43cdaaf0-30f7-405b-b7e0-c8d98b817d6b\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-fix\",\"slug\"